{
  "title": "Combining Runpy and Typing for Production Code in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer demonstrates how to leverage the power of Python's runpy and typing modules for organizing and managing production code in a more efficient manner using Python 3.12+.",
  "key_points": [
    "Utilization of runpy to dynamically import and execute modules in your application",
    "Exploitation of typing for type annotations, enhancing code readability and static analysis capabilities",
    "Application of runpy and typing to create reusable packages or libraries",
    "Introduction of PEP 562 - Module Specs, which enhances the functionality of runpy"
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from typing import List, TypeVar, Callable\nT = TypeVar(\'T\')\n\ndef my_function(arg: T) -> T:\n    ...\n\nmy_module = __import__('mymodule').MyModule # Importing a module dynamically\nmy_instance = my_module.MyClass() # Instantiating the class from the imported module"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from typing import List, Tuple\nfrom runpy import run_module_from_string\n\ndef main():\n    source = 'import sys; sys.path.append(\'./lib\'); from mymodule import MyFunction\n    result: Tuple[int, str] = MyFunction([1, 2, 3]) # Type annotated function call\n    print(result)\nrun_module_from_string(main.__code__, main.__globals__, '__main__') # Running the main function dynamically"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required to take full advantage of typing and runpy enhancements.",
    "PEP 562 - Module Specs, which enhances runpy's functionality, was introduced in Python 3.9."
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "While dynamic importing can improve flexibility, it may introduce runtime dependencies and potential issues with circular imports.",
    "Type annotations do not enforce type checking at runtime, but they do enhance code readability and static analysis capabilities."
  ]
}
